'''''Last Week Tonight with John Oliver''''' is an American [[late-night talk show|late-night talk]] and [[news satire]] television program airing on Sundays on [[HBO]] in the United States and [[HBO Canada]], and on Mondays (originally Tuesdays) on [[Sky Atlantic]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name="order">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=February 12, 2014 |title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |deadurl=no |website=[[Deadline.com]] |publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]] |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/ |archivedate=February 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 12, 2014 }}</ref> The half-hour-long<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|title=John Oliver's HBO Series Gets Name, April Premiere|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/john-olivers-hbo-series-gets-679764|accessdate=March 10, 2014|publisher=[[hollywoodreporter.com]]|date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> show premiered on Sunday, April 27, 2014, and is hosted by comedian [[John Oliver (comedian)|John Oliver]]. ''Last Week Tonight'' shares some similarities with [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[The Daily Show|The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'', where Oliver was previously [[List of The Daily Show correspondents|featured as a correspondent]] and fill-in host, as it takes a satirical look at news, politics and current events on a weekly basis.<ref name="order"/>

Oliver has said that he has full [[Artistic freedom|creative freedom]], including free rein to criticize corporations. His initial contract with HBO was for two years with an option for extension.<ref name="freedom">{{cite web|last=Guthrie |first= Marisa |title= John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The [[Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=19 April 2014|date=16 April 2014}}</ref> In February 2015, it was announced that the show has been renewed for two additional seasons of 35 episodes each.<ref name="time">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/3712367/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-renewed |title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver Gets 2 More Seasons |last=Luckerson |first=Victor |publisher=''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' |date=February 18, 2015 |accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Oliver and HBO programming president Michael Lombardo have discussed extending the show from half an hour to a full hour and airing more than once a week after Oliver "gets his feet under him".<ref name="freedom"/>

==Production==
Oliver described his preparations for the show to an interviewer for ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'': "... I basically have to watch everything. The only thing I kind of watch for pleasure is [[Fareed Zakaria GPS|Fareed Zakaria's show]] on Sundays... That and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' I watch for pleasure, or maybe ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]''... I have a TV on in my office all the time and I'll generally flick around on that from [[CNN]], [[Fox News Channel|Fox]], [[MSNBC]], [[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg]], [[CNBC]], [[Al Jazeera America|Al Jazeera]]... I'm watching with a certain thing in mind and that is how to see a story told badly."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/05/john-oliver-what-i-read/361405/ |author= Zuckerman, Esther |date= May 1, 2014 |title= John Oliver: What I Read |publisher= ''[[The Atlantic#The Wire|The Wire]]'' |accessdate= May 4, 2014}}</ref>

He admitted to another interviewer that he is concerned about dealing with [[News#Newsworthiness|old news]]: "If something happens on a Monday, realistically all the meat is going to be picked off that bone by the time it gets to us - there's probably barely a point in doing it... I think we'll be attracted to some extent by stories that are off the grid... Our show may end up skewing more international in terms of stories."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unfetteredequality.com/2014/08/13/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-changing-journalism-for-the-better |title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Changing journalism for the better |last=Hoxie |first=Angie |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref>

[[Tim Carvell]], executive producer of ''Last Week Tonight'', explained to an interviewer how the cast and crew deal with a half hour of Oliver speaking without any [[Television advertisement|commercial]] breaks.<ref name="usnews">{{cite web |url= http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/04/22/5-things-to-know-about-last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver |author= Sneed, Tierney |date= April 22, 2014 |title= Why ''Last Week Tonight'' Will Not Just Be ''The Daily Show'' on Sundays |publisher= ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' |accessdate= May 4, 2014}}</ref> {{Quotation|"Structural considerations are leading to changes in the content in the show that will inherently make it different from ''The Daily Show''... We realized early on, you don't necessarily want to hear anybody talk to you for a half an hour straight – even John, who is very charming – so we are constructing these little, produced comedy elements that will serve the function of commercial breaks throughout the show, which will let us get out of the studio, get us away from John's voice and break the show up a bit."}} Carvell also revealed that HBO gave them freedom in choosing guests for the show, advising them not to feel obligated to feature celebrities.<ref name="usnews" /> 
When asked by an interviewer about "correspondents" such as those featured on ''The Daily Show'', Oliver replied, "we're not going to be a parody news show, so no people pretending to be journalists."<ref>{{cite web |url= https://tv.yahoo.com/blogs/tv-news/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-interview-two-days-later-222215388.html |author= |date= |title='Last Week Tonight,' Two Days Later: John Oliver on His First Show, Dream Guests, and Old White Racists  |publisher= |accessdate= May 4, 2014}}</ref>

In February 2015, it was announced that the show has been renewed for two additional seasons of 35 episodes each.<ref name="time" />

